data.title: Singer Love overdoses
data.meta_description: Rock singer Courtney Love was treated at a Seattle hospital over the weekend after an apparent overdose of prescription drugs, officials said Monday. Emergency workers were called early Sunday...
data.text:
Rock singer Courtney Love was treated at a Seattle hospital over the weekend after an apparent overdose of prescription drugs, officials said Monday. Emergency workers were called early Sunday to Love's multimillion-dollar home overlooking Lake Washington in Seattle, where her husband Kurt Cobain committed suicide at age 27 last year. They found Love unconscious, police spokesman Sean O'Donnell said. He said Love, 30, had taken prescription medication on a flight from New York, causing her to become groggy, according to a witness. She needed to be helped from the plane and was "unconscious and unresponsive" by the time she arrived home. Love, lead singer of the band Hole, was taken to Harborview Medical Center, where she spent 12 hours before she was released.

In other news . . .

At 10 tonight, MTV will air the premiere of Scream, the anti-media single from Michael Jackson's upcoming CD, HIStory: Past Present Future Book 1.

Winston Groom mailed his Forrest Gump sequel to Pocket Books over the weekend from his Alabama home. Gump & Co., featuring the title character and his son, will be pushed into rapid production so that 600,000 copies will be in stores by late August. Movie rights have reportedly gone for $1-million.

Actor Christopher Reeve, paralyzed after breaking his neck in a horseback-riding accident, continues to show improvement and is eating well, his doctor said Monday.

R.E.M. will make a rare TV stop when they appear on Late Show With David Letterman on June 23.

Speaking of Dave, as of Monday night's Late Show, he has moved the home office of his Top 10 list from Sioux City, Iowa, to Grand Rapids, Mich.

Daniel Baldwin, who has played Detective Beau Felton on NBC's Homicide: Life on the Street for three seasons, won't be back for a fourth. He plans to focus on feature films.

The USA Network has canceled TekWar. The William Shatner series will complete its run on Aug. 12.
